---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import InteractiveChecklist from '../../components/InteractiveChecklist.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="The AI Security Leadership Checklist"
  description="50 questions every CISO, CTO, and CIO should be able to answer about their organization's AI security posture."
  category="Governance & Leadership"
  readingTime="15 min read"
>

<div class="callout callout-info">
  <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
  <p>This checklist is designed for leadership conversations, board reporting, and audit preparation — not for engineers. Each item should be answerable by your AI governance lead without digging through technical documentation.</p>
</div>

<p>Use this checklist in three ways: as a gap analysis to find what you don't know, as a board preparation tool to demonstrate AI governance maturity, and as a recurring quarterly review to track progress over time. Your progress is saved automatically in this browser.</p>

<InteractiveChecklist
  storageKey="leadership-checklist-2025"
  groups={[
    {
      title: "1. AI Inventory & Visibility",
      items: [
        "We have a complete, maintained inventory of every AI system deployed in our organization (including shadow AI and departmental tools)",
        "We know which AI models each system uses, which versions, and which providers supply them",
        "We have a process for employees to request AI tools — and a policy for what happens when they use unapproved tools anyway",
        "We can identify every API key or credential that gives access to external AI providers, and who controls each one",
        "We receive alerts when AI usage significantly exceeds normal patterns (volume, cost, new models accessed)",
        "We have mapped which business processes depend on AI, and what happens if each one fails",
        "We review and update our AI inventory at least quarterly"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "2. Agent Security & Permissions",
      items: [
        "Every AI agent in production has documented permissions — exactly what data, systems, and APIs it can access",
        "Our agents follow the principle of least privilege: they have access to what they need, nothing more",
        "We have a process for reviewing and approving new permissions before agents are granted them",
        "Code-executing agents run in isolated sandbox environments, not directly on production infrastructure",
        "We can revoke an agent's access to any system within minutes if a security incident occurs",
        "We have tested what happens when an agent's tool call fails — does it degrade gracefully or take a dangerous fallback path?",
        "We have documented which agent actions are irreversible, and those actions require human approval before execution",
        "We review agent permissions at least quarterly and remove permissions that are no longer needed"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "3. Data & Privacy Protection",
      items: [
        "We know what categories of data flow through our AI systems (PII, financial data, health records, confidential IP)",
        "We have controls in place to prevent sensitive personal data from being sent to AI models without appropriate safeguards",
        "We can demonstrate that our AI data handling complies with GDPR, CCPA, or other applicable privacy regulations",
        "We have reviewed the data retention and training policies of every AI provider we use",
        "We have a process for responding to a data subject access request that includes AI-processed data",
        "We know whether our AI provider uses our data to train their models, and we have reviewed and accepted or rejected that policy",
        "We have audit logs showing what data was sent to AI systems and when"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "4. Vendor & Supply Chain",
      items: [
        "We have conducted security due diligence on every AI provider we use, including reviewing their SOC 2 reports or equivalent",
        "We have contracts with AI providers that include security, confidentiality, and incident notification requirements",
        "We maintain an approved list of AI plugins and tools; only approved items are used in production",
        "All plugin and dependency versions are pinned — we do not use auto-update in production AI systems",
        "We have a process for reviewing plugin updates before they are deployed",
        "We receive security notifications from our key AI vendors and have a process to act on them",
        "We have assessed what happens to our operations if our primary AI provider has an outage or discontinues a model"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "5. Governance & Compliance",
      items: [
        "We have an AI security policy that has been reviewed and approved by leadership",
        "Accountability for AI security is clearly assigned — there is a named owner, not a committee with shared responsibility",
        "Our AI uses have been mapped to our compliance obligations (financial regulations, healthcare regulations, sector-specific requirements)",
        "We have documented our approach to AI risk assessment and can demonstrate it to auditors or regulators",
        "We have a process for evaluating new AI capabilities or use cases before they go to production",
        "Leadership receives regular reporting on AI security posture — at least quarterly",
        "We have conducted at least one board-level discussion about AI risk in the last 12 months",
        "Our AI governance framework has been reviewed against NIST AI RMF or a comparable standard"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "6. Human Oversight",
      items: [
        "For every consequential AI action, we can state whether it is human-in-the-loop, human-on-the-loop, or post-hoc review — and why",
        "Our oversight requirements are technically enforced, not just policy-based",
        "We have a way to monitor whether human oversight is actually happening (review times, pushback rates, escalations)",
        "We have conducted a tabletop exercise simulating an AI system failure or attack in the last 12 months",
        "Our people who review AI outputs are trained to avoid automation bias — rubber-stamping without real scrutiny",
        "We have defined escalation paths for when an AI agent encounters situations outside its designed scope",
        "We can answer: what is the maximum harm an AI agent can cause before a human has the opportunity to intervene?"
      ]
    },
    {
      title: "7. Incident Response",
      items: [
        "We have a written AI incident response plan that covers prompt injection, data exfiltration, model misbehavior, and supply chain compromise",
        "Our security team knows how to collect and preserve evidence from an AI system incident",
        "We have defined what constitutes an AI security incident requiring escalation versus routine monitoring",
        "We have practiced our AI incident response at least once through a tabletop or simulation exercise",
        "We know our regulatory notification obligations if an AI system is involved in a data breach",
        "We have a process for communicating with affected users or customers if an AI incident impacts them",
        "After any AI incident or near-miss, we conduct a blameless post-mortem and update our controls"
      ]
    }
  ]}
/>

<div class="defense-section">
  <h3>Scoring Guide for Leadership Conversations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>40–50 items checked:</strong> Strong AI security posture. Maintain cadence and look ahead to emerging capabilities (multi-agent systems, computer use).</li>
    <li><strong>25–39 items checked:</strong> Developing posture. Prioritize the unchecked items by risk — agent permissions and data protection first.</li>
    <li><strong>10–24 items checked:</strong> Early stage. Start with inventory and visibility — you cannot govern what you cannot see.</li>
    <li><strong>Under 10 items checked:</strong> Significant gaps exist. Treat AI security as a priority initiative, not a background task.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>No organization checks all 50 immediately. The value is in knowing your gaps — and having a plan to close them.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout callout-warning">
  <span class="callout-icon">⚠️</span>
  <p><strong>A note on "we have a policy for that":</strong> Policies that aren't technically enforced are not controls. Throughout this checklist, distinguish between "we have written a policy" and "we have verified the policy is being followed." The former provides legal cover; the latter provides security.</p>
</div>

</ContentLayout>
